<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-06-27T21:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-06-27T21:00:00-05:00" n="242" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d242">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.9414/8: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Second Secretary of Legation in China</hi>
                                (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Atcheson</hi></persName>)
                                <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-06-28T10:00:00+08:00">June 28, 1935—10
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received June 28—4:58 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>185. My 177, June 22, 10 a.m. Ministers of Industries and Navy confirm
                            remarks of officials previously mentioned. Both state Pratas Reef is of
                            no real value and could not be used for naval or aviation station.
                            According to the latter the sea frequently washes over it and while the
                            Chinese Navy maintains a weather report broadcasting station there a
                            former lighthouse has been abandoned.</p>
                        <p>To the Department and Legation.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Atcheson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
